    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-finding-logarithms-using-tables-and-calculators" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
        <title>Finding Logarithms Using Tables and Calculators</title>
        <objectives component="outcomes">
            <introduction xml:id="auto_unhjcsu5">
                <p xml:id="auto_o53r3u05">
                <dl>
                    <li xml:id="auto_xdvzwziw">
                        <title>Strand</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_k39x2npm">
                            1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ntvub143">
                        <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_433esdxi">
                            1.2 Indices and Logarithms
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_6qp91duw">
                        <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_w8tw5v19">
                            Determine common logarithms of numbers from mathematical tables and calculators
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ybh0vdu7" component="lesson-plan">
                        <title>Grade Level</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_rbybnjo5">
                            10
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_v664nics" component="lesson-plan">
                        <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_adsn9l7a">
                            40 minutes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_r2vsicn5" component="lesson-plan">
                    <p xml:id="auto_2386h1ia"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_c07rkf1r">
                            <p xml:id="auto_7hb991vf">
                                <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand the structure of logarithm tables, including characteristic, mantissa, and mean difference columns.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_dapwzfbt">
                            <p xml:id="auto_j9a6go19">
                                <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Use logarithm tables and calculators to find common logarithms (base 10) of numbers greater than 1 and less than 1.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_5uaems0c">
                            <p xml:id="auto_zaoi7rhc">
                                <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply logarithm skills to solve real-world problems involving large and small numbers.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                    </p>
                </p>
            </introduction>
        </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
            <!-- Link to blurb -->
            <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

            <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
                <sidebyside>
                    <p xml:id="auto_54oxwmdm">
                        <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/indices-and-logarithms/finding-logarithms-using-tables-and-calculators.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_vt0pvmav">
                        <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/indices-and-logarithms/step-by-step-guide_finding-logarithms-using-tables-and-calculators.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                    </p>
                </sidebyside>
            </sbsgroup>
        </axiom>
        <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery / Engage &amp; Explore</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_e1vraywo">
                <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_9z7l5wjz">
                <alert>Objective:</alert> To explore logarithm tables and discover patterns in finding logarithms.
            </p>
        </axiom>

         <activity xml:id="auto_nvhpz580">
            <p xml:id="auto_rmzz0co3">
                <term>Understanding the Table Structure</term>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_n7cosnen">
                        <p xml:id="auto_7ilbji10">
                            Examine your logarithm table. What do you notice about its structure?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_77fpgqkp">
                        <p xml:id="auto_4iigzbhb">
                            Identify the following parts:
                            <ul>
                                <li xml:id="auto_x8yu2icc">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_csbd5y7i">
                                        The first column, titled <alert>Integer</alert>, which contains the numbers <m>10</m><ndash/><m>99</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_pxtaugpy">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_68em20xb">
                                        The middle columns, titled <alert>First Decimal</alert>, which contains the digits <m>0</m><ndash/><m>9</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_wphcl01c">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_61ip6o6p">
                                        The right columns, titled <alert>Mean Difference</alert>, which contains the digits <m>0</m><ndash/><m>9</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_8u2cukwu">
                        <p xml:id="auto_npw706g1">
                            What do you think each part represents?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_m6u0nih5">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ipxn4efg">
                            What happens to the numbers in the table as you go down the middle columns (the first decimal columns)? Or across the middle columns (i.e. from <m>0</m> to <m>9</m>?)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_xhse3awy">
                        <p xml:id="auto_qktqyjrn">
                            What happens to the numbers in the table as you go down the right columns (the mean difference columns)? Or across the right columns (i.e. from <m>0</m> to <m>9</m>?)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </activity>

         <p xml:id="auto_13svgqo9">
            <term>Using Logarithm Tables</term>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_wltpymms">
            In Grade <m>8</m>, you learned how to use mathematical tables to find squares, square roots, and reciprocals of numbers. Here we will use the mathematical tables to determine logarithms to base <m>10</m>.
        </p>
        <table xml:id="log-table">
            <title>Base 10 Logarithm Table</title>
            <xi:include href="log-table.ptx"/>
        </table>

       
        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction / Explain</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_qixf0cid">
                <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_g5y0hk0f">
                <alert>Objective:</alert> To formalize the procedure for finding common logarithms.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_omhq9b0l">
                <alert>Key Takeaways:</alert>
            </p>
            
            <p xml:id="auto_3k7yt4pp">
                <alert>Structure of a Common Logarithm:</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ym00l4b5">
                Every common logarithm has two parts:
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_776tyiy9"><p xml:id="auto_lgf1egdj">Characteristic: The integer part (determined by the position of the decimal point)</p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_swdoenl1"><p xml:id="auto_2uwprodv">Mantissa: The decimal part (found from the logarithm table)</p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_2w9leou0">
                <alert>Finding the Characteristic:</alert>
            </p>
            <tabular bottom="medium" top="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell>Number Type</cell>
                    <cell>Rule</cell>
                    <cell>Example</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Numbers <m>\geq 1</m></cell>
                    <cell>Characteristic <m>=</m> (digits before decimal) <m>- 1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>472.8 \rightarrow \text{Char} = 3 - 1 = 2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Numbers <m>&lt; 1</m></cell>
                    <cell>Characteristic <m>= -</m>(zeros after decimal <m>+ 1</m>)</cell>
                    <cell><m>0.00534 \rightarrow \text{Char} = -(2 + 1) = -3 \;(\text{written as} \;\bar{3})</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p xml:id="auto_t2bf70ky">
                <alert>Finding the Mantissa (5-Step Process):</alert>
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_1ur5lmt4"><p xml:id="auto_20nbtlq7">Write the number in standard form (<m>A \times 10^n</m> where <m>1 \le A &lt; 10</m>)</p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ud7u09y0"><p xml:id="auto_4wdnd0f8">Locate the first two digits in the first column of the log table</p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_y8sjk61n"><p xml:id="auto_0y4qq5c1">Move across to the column for the third digit</p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_fapbi5xc"><p xml:id="auto_xavv4b0z">Add the mean difference for the fourth digit (if applicable)</p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_vlew3lc2"><p xml:id="auto_iqm0ww3w">Combine characteristic + mantissa</p></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_krh6qnxt">
                <alert>Bar Notation for Negative Characteristics:</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ayf7or5d">
                When the characteristic is negative, we write it with a bar over the number:
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_pfr1mxgn"><p xml:id="auto_f0nwd35p"><m>\bar{3}.7272</m> means <m>-3 + 0.7272 = -2.2728</m></p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_jopguwqt"><p xml:id="auto_iwxn71c1">The bar only applies to the characteristic, NOT the mantissa</p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_xiq1rmxl">
                <alert>Addressing Misconceptions:</alert> <q>Remember: The mantissa is ALWAYS positive. Only the characteristic can be negative. Also, always verify your table reading with a calculator when possible.</q>
            </p>
        </axiom>
<insight xml:id="auto_03uxnt0p">
            <p xml:id="auto_hwcnk6dg">
                Structure of a Common Logarithm:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_qd9hc3io">
                Every common logarithm has two parts:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_f25d3mtz">
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_iieb8t9e">
                        <p xml:id="auto_i0xj6fn4">
                            Characteristic: The integer part (determined by the position of the decimal point)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_e33p9az4">
                        <p xml:id="auto_epbykow2">
                            Mantissa: The decimal part (found from the logarithm table)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_z32vlyac">
                <insert>Finding the Characteristic:</insert>
            </p>
            <tabular bottom="medium" top="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell>Number Type</cell>
                    <cell>Rule</cell>
                    <cell>Example</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Numbers <m> \geq 1</m></cell>
                    <cell>Characteristic <m>=</m> (digits before decimal) <m>-1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>472.8 \rightarrow \text{Char} = 3 - 1 = 2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Numbers <m>&lt; 1</m></cell>
                    <cell>Characteristic  <m> = -</m>(zeros after decimal <m>+ 1</m>)</cell>
                    <cell><m>0.00534 \rightarrow \text{Char} = -(2 + 1) = -3 \;(\text{written as} \;\bar{3})</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p xml:id="auto_tt4134x3">
                <alert>Finding the Mantissa (5-Step Process):</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_i5zexlww">
                <ol marker="1.">
                    <li xml:id="auto_qzctaviv">
                        <p xml:id="auto_5oyd8npb">
                            Move the decimal so that there are only two digits to the left of it.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_jt98z9gm">
                        <p xml:id="auto_dskkr93l">
                            Locate the row corresponding to the first two digits (the <alert>integer</alert>) in the table.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_gzzksnia">
                        <p xml:id="auto_7dylk60h">
                            Move across to the column for the first decimal digit, and write down the main part of he mantissa where the row and column intersect.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_4ow41wk3">
                        <p xml:id="auto_iesl76mc">
                            Use the second decimal digit to find the mean difference column in the table and add the value in the corresponding row to the main part of the mantissa.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_bjdmczyz">
                        <p xml:id="auto_i9df7tri">
                            Combine characteristic and mantissa, subtracting if necessary.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ih8ggxze">
                <alert>Bar Notation for Negative Characteristics:</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_etjkf5eo">
                When the characteristic is negative, we write it with a bar over the number:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_3b3njyhx">
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_69nclnxl">
                        <p xml:id="auto_z71qjurc">
                            <m>\bar{3}.7272 = -3 + 0.7272 = -2.2728</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ddjnpts7">
                        <p xml:id="auto_3tz5se1e">
                            The bar only applies to the characteristic, NOT the mantissa
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_8zwd97zh">
                <alert>Remember:</alert> The mantissa is ALWAYS positive. Only the characteristic can be negative. Also, always verify your table reading with a calculator when possible.
            </p>
        </insight>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_y548hka3">
                <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_4bn5oy4y">
                <alert>Objective:</alert> To apply logarithm table skills to find common logarithms.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_36aep5wk">
                <alert>Learning Experience:</alert> Students work through worked examples finding <m>\log(472.8)</m> and <m>\log(0.00534)</m>, applying the 5-step process for each. They identify the characteristic, find the mantissa from the log table, apply mean differences, and combine the results.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_qo4zfaah">
                <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> The teacher monitors students, emphasizing the importance of correctly identifying the characteristic and reading the table accurately.
            </p>
        </axiom>

        <example xml:id="auto_k7dg6aav">
            <statement>
            <title>Finding Logs Using the Table</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_e1km94ha">
                Use the table to find:
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_3ziokiaj">
                        <m>\log_{10}(14.67)</m>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_tbow89ka">
                        <m>\log_{10}(146.7)</m>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_5z3f7h4n">
                        <m>\log_{10}(0.01467)</m>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_3wjpetbx">
                You may find <xref ref="fig-finding-logs"/> helpful:
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-finding-logs">
                <caption>Help finding <m>\log_{10}(14.67)</m></caption>
                <image source="finding-logs.png">                
                </image>
            </figure>
            </statement>    
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_bjtjdjyo">
                        <p xml:id="auto_dknf3ztk">
                            To use the table, we need to split <m>14.67</m> into three components.
                            <ul>
                                <li xml:id="auto_rusohf7m">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_74787xqz">
                                        The <alert>integer</alert> part, left of the decimal, is <m>14</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_p1y2tb5e">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_44qqoybt">
                                        The <alert>first decmial</alert>, which is the digit immediately to the right of the decimal: <m>6</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_rylap9ka">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_9w0wt3fd">
                                        The <alert>second decimal</alert>, following the first decimal, is <m>7</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_de8lt5jn">
                            We can use the table to find the <term>mantissa</term> of <m>\log_{10}(14.67)</m>. This is the decimal part of the answer. The steps are as follows:
                        </p>
                        <ol marker="1.">
                            <li xml:id="auto_bdl5ljyg">
                                <p xml:id="auto_f7gvltiz">
                                    As shown in <xref ref="fig-finding-logs"/>, we use the <alert>integer</alert> part <m>(14)</m> to find which row of the table we need, which is highlighted in <m>\color{purple}{\text{purple}}</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_1y992753">
                                <p xml:id="auto_daty3nnz">
                                    Next, we use the <alert>first decimal</alert> <m>(6)</m> to find the column, which is highlighted in <m>\color{green}{\text{green}}</m>. Where the row and column overlap (show in the <m>\color{red}{\text{red}}</m> box) we have the main part of the mantissa: <m>1644</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_szgo7s11">
                                <p xml:id="auto_cxg52q9s">
                                    However, we are taking <m>\log_{10}(14.67)</m>, not just <m>\log_{10}(14.6)</m>. So we need to adjust our mantissa using the <alert>second decimal</alert> <m>(7)</m>. Locate the column for this under the <alert>Mean Difference</alert> part of the table (coloured in <m>\color{blue}{\text{blue}}</m>), and find where this intersects with the row from before. This is shown in <m>\color{orange}{\text{orange}}</m>, with mean difference <m>21</m> in our example.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_wo1or5lw">
                                <p xml:id="auto_md4atr38">
                                    We add this adjustment to the main part of our mantissa, to get the mantissa as: <m>1644+21 = 1665</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                        <p xml:id="auto_w5j732y3">
                            Thus, we know that <m>\log_{10}(14.67) = X.1665</m>. But we need to find <m>X</m>, called the <term>characteristic</term>.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_4lmt1r8u">
                            There is an easy shortcut:
                            <md>
                                X = \text{Number of digits before the decimal} - 1
                            </md>
                            So with <m>14.67</m>, we have 2 digits before the decimal (<m>14</m> has two digits), so <m>X = 2 - 1 = 1</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_mk1o725g">
                            Thus <m>\log_{10}(14.67) = 1.665</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_58beg3bn">
                        <p xml:id="auto_lvwjkvbp">
                            If we try the same procedure as (a) with <m>\log_{10}(146.7)</m>, we run into a problem: there's no row for <m>146</m>! The table only works directly for <m>\log_{10}(x)</m> when <m>10 \le x &lt; 100 </m>.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_ts3gtpqh">
                            Remembering our logarithm laws from <xref ref="subsubsec-logarithms-of-products-and-ratios" text="title"/>, we know that:
                            <md>
                                \log_{10}(146.7) = \log_{10}\left(10 \times 14.67\right) = \log_{10}(10) + \log_{10}(14.67)
                            </md>
                            So we can shift the decimal so there are only two digits to the left of it <m>(14)</m>, and calculate the mantissa using the same procedure as (a).
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_eo2d0e92">
                            You now need to find the mantissa of <m>\log_{10}(14.67)</m> using the steps in (a). As we've just done that, we'll reuse our answer of <m>.1665</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_ahl3220e">
                            For the characteristic, the same rule applies:
                            <md>
                                X = \text{Number of digits before the decimal} - 1
                            </md>
                            So with our <em>original</em> number <m>146.77</m>, we have 3 digits before the decimal (<m>146</m> has three digits), so <m>X = 3 - 1 = 2</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_xm18nxqq">
                            Why is this still true? Since <m>146.7</m> has an extra digit left of the decimal than <m>14.67</m>, we get a <m>\log_{10}(10)</m> term from the logarithm rule. And <m>\log_{10}(10) = 1</m>, so our characteristic is bigger by <m>1</m>, the exact number of extra digits.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_qek7hvr9">
                            Hence combining the characteristic and the mantissa, we have <m>\log_{10}(146.7) = 2.1665</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <p xml:id="auto_kqm0xic6">
                        We also need to transform <m>\log_{10}(0.01467)</m> to get it into the correct form. We can use the logarithm rule for quotients to write:
                        <md>
                            \log_{10}(0.01467) = \log_{10}\left(\frac{14.67}{1000}) = \log_{10}(14.67) - \log_{10}(1000)
                        </md>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_daxxqxb6">
                        Like (a) and (b), our mantissa is <m>.1665</m>. But now our characteristic will be <em>negative</em>:
                        <md>
                            X = -\left(\text{Number of zeros after the decimal} + 1\right)
                        </md>
                        In this case, we have 1 zero after the decimal, so <m>X = -(2 + 1) = -3</m>. We write this as <m>\bar{3}</m> to indicate that it's negative.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_y8h29tat">
                        So we have <m>\log_{10}(0.01467) = \bar{3}.1665</m>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_yi84218q">
                        It's typical to write this answer using negatives. To do this, we need to subtract the mantissa from the characteristic:
                        <md>
                            \log_{10}(0.01467) = -3 + 0.1665 = -2.8335
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </example>
        

        <example xml:id="auto_pz9erh8d">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_zsai5pza">
                    Find <m>\log (472.8)</m> using a logarithm table.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_oz7pqsnr">
                    First, we split <m>472.8</m> into its components. Since the table only works for numbers with two digits before the decimal, we shift the decimal to get <m>47.28</m>:
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_h40t44s6"><p xml:id="auto_cn70qk4e"><alert>Integer</alert>: <m>47</m></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_23oylqrz"><p xml:id="auto_u8e2r8e1"><alert>First decimal</alert>: <m>2</m></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_o2294kr5"><p xml:id="auto_2mgrz11t"><alert>Second decimal</alert>: <m>8</m></p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_8o5tsx0g">
                    From the table: row <m>47</m>, first decimal column <m>2</m> gives <m>6739</m>. The mean difference for <m>8</m> is <m>7</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_fx8glb6t">
                    So the mantissa is <m>6739 + 7 = 6746</m>, i.e. <m>.6746</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_arto7bcp">
                    For the characteristic: <m>472.8</m> has <m>3</m> digits before the decimal, so <m>X = 3 - 1 = 2</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_lmaiwnci">
                    Therefore:
                    <me>
                        \log (472.8) = 2.6746
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_1svibwmw">
                    Using a calculator, we can confirm that <m>\log (472.8) \approx 2.6747</m>, which closely matches the table value.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="auto_lr4e3wd0">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_r6es835q">
                    Use logarithm tables to find <m>\log 0.00534</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_cvs6zw14">
                    First, we shift the decimal to get two digits before it: <m>53.4</m>.
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_l3vwynnu"><p xml:id="auto_gdmetwx7"><alert>Integer</alert>: <m>53</m></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_8c6pz98f"><p xml:id="auto_6m4hlbau"><alert>First decimal</alert>: <m>4</m></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_cwxndx0y"><p xml:id="auto_295zxr0z">No second decimal.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_2atzq3tp">
                    From the table: row <m>53</m>, first decimal column <m>4</m> gives <m>7275</m>. No mean difference is needed.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_nm8ph3ps">
                    So the mantissa is <m>.7275</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_sclblxyx">
                    For the characteristic: <m>0.00534</m> has <m>2</m> zeros after the decimal point, so <m>X = -(2 + 1) = -3</m>, written as <m>\bar{3}</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_awo5o7b1">
                    Therefore:
                    <me>
                        \log (0.00534) = \bar{3}.7275
                    </me>
                    which, as a negative number, is <m>-3 + 0.7275 = -2.2725</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_yypd347m">
                    Using a calculator, we can confirm that <m>\log (0.00534) \approx -2.2725</m>, matching the table value.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 4: Assessment / Evaluate (Exit Ticket)</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_2okorhrj">
                <alert>Objective:</alert> To formatively assess individual student understanding.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_is320f9f">
                <alert>Learning Experience:</alert> Students complete exit ticket questions:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_1gf4dsun"><p xml:id="auto_ixv3xb7w">Express numbers in standard form (e.g., 4820, 37.6, 672000, 0.000485)</p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_012lsxu3"><p xml:id="auto_f0nqm2fu">Use a logarithm table to find the logarithm of numbers (e.g., 0.00893, 3140, 52.7, 0.000978)</p></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_xc3mwnru">
                <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge student understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
            </p>
        </axiom>
